<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-limits-and-continuity"
  xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Limits and Continuity</title>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-limits-at-cluster-points">
    <title>Limits at Cluster Points</title>

    <p>
      Let <m>S \subseteq \R</m>, let <m>f \colon S \to \R</m> be a function,
      and let <m>c</m> be a cluster point of <m>S</m>. We say that
      <m>f</m> has <term>limit</term><idx>limit of a function</idx> <m>L \in
      \R</m> at <m>c</m> if for every <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m> there exists
      <m>\delta \gt 0</m> such that whenever <m>x \in S</m> and
      <m>0 \lt |x-c| \lt \delta</m>, we have
      <md>|f(x)-L| \lt \varepsilon.</md>
    </p>

    <p>
      In that case we write
      <md>\lim_{x\to c} f(x)=L</md>
      or, equivalently,
      <md>f(x)\to L \quad \text{as } x\to c.</md>
      These two notations mean exactly the same thing. The second is read as
      “<m>f(x)</m> tends to <m>L</m> as <m>x</m> tends to <m>c</m>.”
    </p>

    <p>
      The condition <m>0 \lt |x-c|</m> is essential: it says that we are only
      looking at points <m>x</m> near <m>c</m> but different from <m>c</m>.
      Thus the existence of <m>\lim_{x\to c} f(x)</m> depends only on the
      values of <m>f</m> arbitrarily close to <m>c</m>, not on the value
      <m>f(c)</m>. In particular, <m>c</m> need not even belong to the domain
      of <m>f</m>.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="eg-limit-at-point-with-hole">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f(x)=x+1</m> on <m>\R \setminus \{1\}</m>. Then
          <m>\lim_{x\to 1} f(x)=2</m>. Indeed, if
          <m>0 \lt |x-1| \lt \varepsilon</m>, then
          <md>|f(x)-2|=|(x+1)-2|=|x-1| \lt \varepsilon.</md>
          This example shows that a limit may exist even when <m>f</m> is not
          defined at the limiting point.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-limit-unique">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>\lim_{x\to c} f(x)</m> exists, then it is unique.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>L_1</m> and <m>L_2</m> are limits of <m>f</m> at
          <m>c</m>. We must show that <m>L_1=L_2</m>. Let
          <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m>. By the definition of limit, there exist
          <m>\delta_i \gt 0</m> such that <m>|f(x)-L_i| \lt \varepsilon</m>
          whenever <m>x \in S</m> and <m>0 \lt |x-c| \lt \delta_i</m>, for
          <m>i=1,2</m>. Thus,

          <md>
            |L_1-L_2| \le |f(x)-L_1| + |f(x)-L_2| \lt 2\varepsilon
          </md>
          for any <m>x \in S</m> with
          <m>0 \lt |x-c| \lt \min\{\delta_1,\delta_2\}</m>. By the definition
          of cluster point, such an <m>x</m> exists. Since
          <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m> was arbitrary, it follows that
          <m>|L_1-L_2|=0</m>. Therefore <m>L_1=L_2</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <p>
      This proposition also explains why we only define
      <m>\lim_{x\to c} f(x)</m> when <m>c</m> is a cluster point of the
      domain. If <m>c</m> were an isolated point of <m>S</m>, then for
      sufficiently small <m>\delta</m> there would be no point <m>x \in S</m>
      with <m>0 \lt |x-c| \lt \delta</m>. The implication in the definition
      would then be automatically true for every real number <m>L</m>, so the
      “limit” would not be unique.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="eg-no-limit-at-isolated-point">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>S=\{0\}</m> and let <m>f(0)=7</m>. If we tried to define a
          limit of <m>f</m> at <m>0</m> using the usual punctured-neighborhood
          condition, then every <m>L \in \R</m> would satisfy it, because
          there are no points <m>x \in S</m> with <m>0 \lt |x| \lt \delta</m>.
          So there is no meaningful notion of limit at that isolated point.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-one-sided-limits">
    <title>Left and Right Limits</title>

    <p>
      Suppose <m>c</m> is a cluster point of <m>S \cap (-\infty,c)</m>. We
      say that <m>f</m> has <term>left limit</term><idx>left limit</idx>
      <m>L</m> at <m>c</m> if for every <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m> there exists
      <m>\delta \gt 0</m> such that whenever <m>x \in S</m> and
      <m>c-\delta \lt x \lt c</m>, we have
      <md>|f(x)-L| \lt \varepsilon.</md>
      We write <m>\lim_{x\to c^-} f(x)=L</m> or <m>f(c^-) = L</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Similarly, if <m>c</m> is a cluster point of
      <m>S \cap (c,\infty)</m>, we say that <m>f</m> has
      <term>right limit</term><idx>right limit</idx> <m>L</m> at <m>c</m> if
      for every <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m> there exists <m>\delta \gt 0</m>
      such that whenever <m>x \in S</m> and <m>c \lt x \lt c+\delta</m>, we
      have <md>|f(x)-L| \lt \varepsilon.</md>
      We write <m>\lim_{x\to c^+} f(x)=L</m> or <m>f(c^+) = L</m>.
    </p>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-two-sided-limit-iff-one-sided-limits">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Assume that <m>c</m> is a cluster point of both
          <m>S \cap (-\infty,c)</m> and <m>S \cap (c,\infty)</m>. Then
          <md>\lim_{x\to c} f(x)=L</md>
          if and only if
          <md>\lim_{x\to c^-} f(x)=L=\lim_{x\to c^+} f(x).</md>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>\lim_{x\to c} f(x)=L</m>. Given
          <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m>, choose <m>\delta \gt 0</m> so that
          <m>|f(x)-L| \lt \varepsilon</m> whenever <m>x \in S</m> and
          <m>0 \lt |x-c| \lt \delta</m>. If <m>c-\delta \lt x \lt c</m>, then
          certainly <m>0 \lt |x-c| \lt \delta</m>, so
          <m>|f(x)-L| \lt \varepsilon</m>. This proves
          <m>\lim_{x\to c^-} f(x)=L</m>. The proof for the right limit is the
          same.
        </p>

        <p>
          Conversely, suppose both one-sided limits exist and are equal to
          <m>L</m>. Given <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m>, choose
          <m>\delta_1,\delta_2 \gt 0</m> so that
          <m>|f(x)-L| \lt \varepsilon</m> whenever <m>x \in S</m> and
          <m>c-\delta_1 \lt x \lt c</m>, and also whenever <m>x \in S</m> and
          <m>c \lt x \lt c+\delta_2</m>. Let
          <m>\delta=\min\{\delta_1,\delta_2\}</m>. If <m>x \in S</m> and
          <m>0 \lt |x-c| \lt \delta</m>, then either <m>x \lt c</m> or
          <m>x \gt c</m>. In the first case <m>c-\delta_1 \lt x \lt c</m>, and
          in the second case <m>c \lt x \lt c+\delta_2</m>. Hence in either
          case <m>|f(x)-L| \lt \varepsilon</m>. Therefore
          <m>\lim_{x\to c} f(x)=L</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <example xml:id="eg-sign-function-one-sided-limits">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Define
          <md>\operatorname{sgn} x=\begin{cases}
          -1 &amp; \text{if } x \lt 0,\\
          1 &amp; \text{if } x \ge 0.
          \end{cases}</md>
          Then
          <m>\lim_{x\to 0^-} \operatorname{sgn} x=-1</m> and
          <m>\lim_{x\to 0^+} \operatorname{sgn} x=1</m>. Since these
          one-sided limits are different, <m>\lim_{x\to 0} \operatorname{sgn}
          x</m> does not exist.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-limit-and-continuity">
    <title>Relation Between Limits and Continuity</title>

    <p>
      The definition of limit ignores the value at the point <m>c</m>,
      whereas continuity compares nearby values with <m>f(c)</m>. Because of
      this, limits and continuity are closely related but not identical.
    </p>

    <proposition xml:id="prop-continuity-iff-limit-equals-value">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f \colon S \to \R</m> and let <m>c \in S</m>. If
          <m>c</m> is a cluster point of <m>S</m>, then <m>f</m> is
          continuous at <m>c</m> if and only if
          <md>\lim_{x\to c} f(x)=f(c).</md>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>f</m> is continuous at <m>c</m>. Let
          <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m> be given. By continuity, there exists
          <m>\delta \gt 0</m> such that
          <m>|f(x)-f(c)| \lt \varepsilon</m> whenever <m>x \in S</m> and
          <m>|x-c| \lt \delta</m>. In particular, this holds whenever
          <m>x \in S</m> and <m>0 \lt |x-c| \lt \delta</m>. Hence
          <m>\lim_{x\to c} f(x)=f(c)</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Conversely, suppose <m>\lim_{x\to c} f(x)=f(c)</m>. Let
          <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m> be given. Then there exists
          <m>\delta \gt 0</m> such that
          <m>|f(x)-f(c)| \lt \varepsilon</m> whenever <m>x \in S</m> and
          <m>0 \lt |x-c| \lt \delta</m>. Now if <m>x \in S</m> and
          <m>|x-c| \lt \delta</m>, then either <m>x=c</m>, in which case
          <m>|f(x)-f(c)|=0</m>, or <m>0 \lt |x-c| \lt \delta</m>, in which
          case <m>|f(x)-f(c)| \lt \varepsilon</m>. Therefore <m>f</m> is
          continuous at <m>c</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>

    <example xml:id="eg-removable-discontinuity">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Define
          <md>f(x)=\begin{cases}
          \dfrac{x^2-1}{x-1} &amp; \text{if } x \neq 1,\\
          0 &amp; \text{if } x=1.
          \end{cases}</md>
          For <m>x \neq 1</m>, we have <m>f(x)=x+1</m>, so
          <m>\lim_{x\to 1} f(x)=2</m>. However, <m>f(1)=0</m>, so
          <m>f</m> is not continuous at <m>1</m>. If we redefine the value at
          <m>1</m> to be <m>2</m>, then the resulting function becomes
          continuous at <m>1</m>. This is the basic model of a
          <term>removable discontinuity</term><idx>removable discontinuity</idx>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-extended-real-limits">
    <title>Limits Involving <m>\pm\infty</m></title>

    <p>
      We now extend the definition of limit to cases where either the point
      approached or the limiting value is allowed to be <m>+\infty</m> or
      <m>-\infty</m>. The set
      <m>\R \cup \{-\infty,+\infty\}</m> is called the
      <term>extended real line</term><idx>extended real line</idx>.
    </p>

    <p>
      First suppose <m>c \in \R</m> is a cluster point of <m>S</m>. We write
      <md>\lim_{x\to c} f(x)=+\infty</md>
      if for every <m>M \in \R</m> there exists <m>\delta \gt 0</m> such that
      whenever <m>x \in S</m> and <m>0 \lt |x-c| \lt \delta</m>, we have
      <m>f(x) \gt M</m>. Similarly, we write
      <md>\lim_{x\to c} f(x)=-\infty</md>
      if for every <m>M \in \R</m> there exists <m>\delta \gt 0</m> such that
      whenever <m>x \in S</m> and <m>0 \lt |x-c| \lt \delta</m>, we have
      <m>f(x) \lt M</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      The one-sided definitions extend in exactly the same way. For example,
      <m>\lim_{x\to c^+} f(x)=+\infty</m> means that for every <m>M \in
      \R</m> there exists <m>\delta \gt 0</m> such that whenever
      <m>x \in S</m> and <m>c \lt x \lt c+\delta</m>, we have
      <m>f(x) \gt M</m>. The other one-sided cases are analogous.
    </p>

    <p>
      Next suppose that <m>S</m> is unbounded above. We write
      <md>\lim_{x\to +\infty} f(x)=L</md>
      for <m>L \in \R</m> if for every <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m> there exists
      <m>A \in \R</m> such that whenever <m>x \in S</m> and <m>x \gt A</m>,
      we have <m>|f(x)-L| \lt \varepsilon</m>. We write
      <md>\lim_{x\to +\infty} f(x)=+\infty</md>
      if for every <m>M \in \R</m> there exists <m>A \in \R</m> such that
      whenever <m>x \in S</m> and <m>x \gt A</m>, we have
      <m>f(x) \gt M</m>. The definition of
      <m>\lim_{x\to +\infty} f(x)=-\infty</m> is analogous.
    </p>

    <p>
      Likewise, if <m>S</m> is unbounded below, we write
      <md>\lim_{x\to -\infty} f(x)=L</md>
      for <m>L \in \R</m> if for every <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m> there exists
      <m>A \in \R</m> such that whenever <m>x \in S</m> and <m>x \lt A</m>,
      we have <m>|f(x)-L| \lt \varepsilon</m>. We define
      <m>\lim_{x\to -\infty} f(x)=+\infty</m> and
      <m>\lim_{x\to -\infty} f(x)=-\infty</m> similarly, by requiring
      <m>f(x)</m> to be eventually larger than any prescribed real number, or
      eventually smaller than any prescribed real number.
    </p>

    <p>
      In each of these cases we also use the corresponding arrow notation:
      <m>f(x)\to L</m> as <m>x\to c</m>, as <m>x\to +\infty</m>, or as
      <m>x\to -\infty</m>. The same uniqueness principle remains valid for
      these extended-real limits as well.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="eg-extended-real-limits">
      <statement>
        <ul>
          <li>
            On <m>\R \setminus \{0\}</m>, we have
            <m>\lim_{x\to 0} \frac{1}{x^2}=+\infty</m>.
          </li>
          <li>
            On <m>\R \setminus \{0\}</m>, we have
            <m>\lim_{x\to 0^+} \frac{1}{x}=+\infty</m> and
            <m>\lim_{x\to 0^-} \frac{1}{x}=-\infty</m>.
          </li>
          <li>
            On <m>(0,\infty)</m>, we have
            <m>\lim_{x\to +\infty} \frac{1}{x}=0</m>.
          </li>
          <li>
            On <m>\R</m>, we have
            <m>\lim_{x\to -\infty} x^2=+\infty</m>.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <p>
      It is often helpful to think of <m>+\infty</m> and <m>-\infty</m> as
      extra endpoints added to the real line. Then the definitions above are
      the natural analogues of ordinary limits at finite cluster points.
    </p>
  </subsection>
</section>
